Just to be a bit picky, Masamune may popularly and generally be considered
to be the best ever swordsmith and is certainly the most famous, but
Muramasa could not be described as the second best by any stretch of the
imagination and he was not connected to Masamune in any way, his swords just
had a bloodthirsty reputation.
Regards
Clive

messages.subject: Re: [samuraihistory] hello its me agin!
messages.msgSnippet: ... *sigh* The people saying samurai still exist are just giving you a hard time. It s called sarcasm. Look into it. The samurai class was abolished in the
messages.messageBody:
--- thenight12_4 <thenight12_4@...> wrote:

> i got confused some of you are saying there is real
> samurai left and
> some of you are saying no

*sigh*

The people saying samurai still exist are just giving
you a hard time. It's called sarcasm. Look into it.

The samurai class was abolished in the early 1870's.
They don't exist by act of law. Someone who was a
samurai in 1870 was no longer a samurai in 1877
because the government of Japan said so. A simple
google search would turn this information up in about
5 seconds.

However, you could also look here--I suggest you do
so, and quickly:

http://www.geocities.com/klancesegall/home.htm

It's required reading before posting on this email
list. And you obviously didn't read it
beforehand--please do so now.

Thanks,

The Mgmt.
